                                                <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.&#8212;<name type="person">Private Henry Baine</name>, <name type="organization">Co. C, 183th
                                                                Pennsylvania Volunteers</name>, aged 19 years, received,
                                                                at the battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="263">Cold Harbor, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-06-03">June 3d,
                                                                                1864</date>, a gunshot wound of head and face, conoidal
                                                  ball entering in front of the meatus auditorius,
                                                  left side, and emerging at nasal eminence,
                                                  involving loss of left eye and partial destruction
                                                  of internal maxillary artery. He was admitted to
                                                  the <name type="hospital" key="172">Emory Hospital</name>, Washington, on <date type="admit" when="1864-06-10">June 10th,
                                                                  1864</date>. Face much swollen; vision destroyed. Cold
                                                  water dressings were applied and tonics
                                                  administered. Patient did well until the evening
                                                  of <date type="injury" when="1864-06-15">June 15th</date>, when secondary h&#230;morrhage took
                                                  place. He lost from four to six pounds of blood,
                                                  necessitating operation. On <date type="operation" when="1864-06-16">June 16th</date>, at ten A.
                                                                M., <name type="person">Surgeon N. R. Moseley</name>, <name type="organization" key="132">U. S. V.</name>, ligated the
                                                  common carotid artery, in superior carotid
                                                  triangle, just below origin of internal maxillary
                                                  artery. He died on <date type="death" when="1864-06-26">June 26th, 1864</date>, from
                                                  exhaustion and debility. The case is reported by
                                                  the operator. </p>
                                                
